snippet.textDisplay: If this pilot was so good he wouldnt have flew. This is a horrible tragedy that has struck the world. Just absolutely astounded that anyone wouldve actually thought of flying in weather like that. This was a horrible mistake. I learned also that there was a tournament they had to get too, and that people needed to be there, kobe was probably like, oh we have to get there quick ya know we’re gonna be late and we cant drive. If you live in the LA county/Ventura county, would know driving at that hour on the 405/101 freeway is traffic heavy. Also the weather is very interesting. Driving from LA to ventura there are, some mornings. Very, Very thick fog layers spread out among different sub cities. Thousand Oaks, Newbury Park, Agoura. If LAPD wasnt flying copters. Then Kobes pilot shouldnt have either. The man had plenty of flight experience to know that this is not the right kind of weather for flying in. ESPECIALLY a helicopter. I think what ultimately led to Kobes death was his drive. I believe Kobe was pushing the pilot to fly because Kobe wanted to see his daughter play and be able to make it to the tournament on time with friends. I just dont think the right decisions were made when it comes to a helicopter flying in crappy weather. If i know ANY pilot, they will not fly in shit weather. Its just common fact and knowledge. Its the same idea when you talk about airplane turbulence. When you go through clouds. Its gonna be a rough time. Now imagine that; but in a much smaller area. The pilot had no control and flipped the chopper over crashed. He picked up sudden speeds and panicked. This is horrible. Kobe was a living legend. Im so glad to say that as a kid i got to see the Mamba strike, but as an adult ill get to say that his legacy will live on forever in the hearts of millions.
